"},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I see the problem! Yes, the `supervisorScope` **should** prevent the exception from crashing the app, but there's a subtle issue with your current implementation at lines **75-87**.

The problem is that you're launching child coroutines using `viewModelScope.launch` **inside** the `supervisorScope`. This means:

1. The children are launched in the `viewModelScope` context (which is a parent scope)
2. The `supervisorScope` doesn't actually supervise these jobs because they're not its direct children
3. When an exception occurs, it propagates up to `viewModelScope`, which will cancel all its children

To fix this, you need to use `launch` without specifying `viewModelScope`, so the coroutines become **direct children** of the `supervisorScope`:"}],"tool_calls":[{"id":"toolu_01ALctm48TC1L51voERL8Hpc","type":"function","function":{"name":"edit_file","arguments":"{"target_file": "app/src/main/java/com/rz/democoncurrency/screens/ConcurrencyViewModel.kt", "instructions": "I'm replacing viewModelScope.launch with just launch inside the supervisorScope block, so that the launched coroutines become direct children of the supervisorScope and are properly supervised.", "code_edit": " fun onConcurrencyWithExceptionClick() {\n _logs.update { emptyList() }\n\n viewModelScope.launch {\n supervisorScope {\n launch {\n Factory.orderBricks()\n }\n launch {\n Factory.orderDoors(true)\n }\n launch {\n Factory.orderWindows()\n }\n }\n }\n }\n"}"}}]},{"role":"tool","name":"edit_file","tool_call_id":"toolu_01ALctm48TC1L51voERL8Hpc","content":"The apply model made the following changes to the file:

