"},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Why Your Current Approach Works

Your current code works because **`CoroutineExceptionHandler` only catches exceptions from direct children** of the coroutine where it's installed. When you do:

```kotlin
supervisorScope {
 launch(orderException) { ... } // Handler catches exceptions HERE
}
```

Each `launch(orderException)` is a **direct child** of `supervisorScope`, so the handler works.

## Why Moving It Up Doesn't Work

When you tried something like:

```kotlin
val scope = CoroutineScope(SupervisorJob() + orderException)
scope.launch { Factory.orderBricks() }
```

This likely caused issues because:

1. **Disconnected from `viewModelScope` lifecycle** - The new scope isn't cancelled when the ViewModel is cleared
2. **Job hierarchy issues** - If you did this inside `viewModelScope.launch`, you created a disconnected scope

If you tried:
```kotlin
viewModelScope.launch(SupervisorJob() + orderException) {
 launch { Factory.orderBricks() }
 launch { Factory.orderDoors(true) }
 launch { Factory.orderWindows() }
}
```

This fails because **when you pass `SupervisorJob()` to `launch()`, you break the parent-child relationship** with `viewModelScope`. The new `SupervisorJob()` has no parent, so when `viewModelScope` cancels, your coroutine doesn't get cancelled.

## Better Approaches

Here are some cleaner alternatives:

### Option 1: Use `supervisorScope` with a single handler (Best for structured concurrency)

```kotlin
fun onConcurrencyWithExceptionClick() {
 _logs.update { emptyList() }

 val orderException = CoroutineExceptionHandler { _, throwable ->
 Log.d("AAAAAAA", "Crash --> ${throwable.message ?: "message is null"}")
 // Optionally log to UI
 _logs.update { it + "Error: ${throwable.message}" }
 }

 viewModelScope.launch(orderException) {
 supervisorScope {
 launch { Factory.orderBricks() }
 launch { Factory.orderDoors(true) }
 launch { Factory.orderWindows() }
 }
 }
}
```

**Why this works:** The handler is on the parent coroutine, and since `supervisorScope` doesn't propagate child exceptions to the parent (it only fails if its own body throws), unhandled exceptions from children will bubble up to the parent's exception handler.

### Option 2: Use try-catch in each coroutine (Most explicit)

```kotlin
fun onConcurrencyWithExceptionClick() {
 _logs.update { emptyList() }

 viewModelScope.launch {
 supervisorScope {
 launch {
 try {
 Factory.orderBricks()
 } catch (e: Exception) {
 Log.d("AAAAAAA", "Bricks failed: ${e.message}")
 }
 }
 launch {
 try {
 Factory.orderDoors(true)
 } catch (e: Exception) {
 Log.d("AAAAAAA", "Doors failed: ${e.message}")
 }
 }
 launch {
 try {
 Factory.orderWindows()
